<section class="page-header">
    <h1>Documentation & Whitepaper</h1>
    <p>A deep technical and conceptual explanation of COR’s internal governance engine.</p>
</section>

<section class="content-block">
    <h2>Governance Engine Model</h2>
    <p>COR is built on a layered governance architecture that transforms policies, rules, and oversight structures into executable logic. Each layer is independent yet interoperable, enabling domain‑agnostic governance.</p>
</section>

<section class="content-block">
    <h2>Policy Model</h2>
    <p>Policies are represented as structured objects containing conditions, obligations, prohibitions, and exceptions. COR evaluates these objects in real time to enforce governance boundaries.</p>
</section>

<section class="content-block">
    <h2>Decision Logic</h2>
    <p>Decision pathways define who can authorize actions, under what conditions, and with what escalation. COR ensures every decision follows its defined governance path.</p>
</section>

<section class="content-block">
    <h2>Workflow Enforcement</h2>
    <p>Workflows are governed sequences of actions. COR enforces checkpoints, approvals, and compliance gates to ensure processes follow authorized routes.</p>
</section>

<section class="content-block">
    <h2>Audit Architecture</h2>
    <p>Every rule evaluation, decision, and workflow step is recorded in an immutable audit log. This provides transparency, accountability, and regulatory readiness.</p>
</section>

<section class="content-block">
    <h2>Integration Model</h2>
    <p>COR integrates with external systems through APIs, adapters, and event listeners. It observes, governs, and constrains behavior across heterogeneous environments.</p>
</section>

